4 PART III. PHARMACY BENEFITS MANAGER TRANSPARENCY, FAIR
5 REIMBURSEMENT, AND FIDUCIARY DUTIES
6 SECTION 3.1. Article 56A of Chapter 58 of the General Statutes is amended by
7 adding new sections to read:
8 "§ 58-56A-22. Reporting requirements for transparency.
9 (a) Reports to Commissioner. – No later than May 1 of every year, all pharmacy benefits
10 managers shall report to the Commissioner all of the following information regarding
11 prescription drug benefits specific to insurers within the State with which a pharmacy benefits
12 manager has a contract:
13 (1) The aggregate amount of the rebates that the pharmacy benefits manager
14 received from all drug manufacturers or whole distributers by therapeutic
15 category of prescription drugs. In reporting the aggregate amount of the
16 rebates, the pharmacy benefits manager shall include any utilization discounts
17 it receives from a manufacturer or wholesale distributor.
18 (2) The aggregated amount of difference between the amount paid by the health
19 benefit plan for prescription drugs and the aggregated amount paid to
20 pharmacies for claims paid under the health benefit plan, including
21 point-of-sale and retroactive charges.
22 (3) The spread between aggregate amount paid to pharmacies for prescription
23 drugs and the aggregated amount charged to insurers for prescription drugs.
24 (4) A list of all pharmacies that are under common control or ownership of the
25 pharmacy benefits manager.
26 (5) A pharmacy benefits manager that is affiliated with a retail pharmacy shall
27 provide the aggregated amount of any differences between what the pharmacy
28 benefits manager reimburses or charges affiliated retail pharmacies and what
29 it reimburses or charges non-affiliated retail pharmacies.
30 (6) The aggregate amount of all fees or other assessments, including point-of-sale
31 and retroactive charges, that are imposed on, or collected from, contracted,
32 preferred, or in-network pharmacies. Retroactive charges shall not include any
33 funds recouped from an audit conducted under Part 8 of Article 50 of this
34 Chapter.
35 (7) The aggregate amount of rebates and fees that were passed on to either the
36 insurer with which the pharmacy benefits manager is contracted or an insured
37 at the point-of-sale of a prescription drug.
38 (8) The highest, lowest, and mean aggregate percentages for retained rebates by
39 the pharmacy benefits manager.
40 (b) Reports to Insurers. – Upon the request of an insurer with which a pharmacy benefits
41 manager is contracted, the pharmacy benefits manager shall prepare an annual report that
42 discloses the total amount of the difference between the amount paid by each contracted health
43 benefit plan offered by the insurer for prescription drugs and the aggregated amount paid to
44 pharmacies for claims paid under each applicable health benefit plan.
45 (c) Confidentiality of Data. – Information contained in a report required under this
46 section shall not reveal any personally identifiable information of any insured. Information
47 contained in this report is not considered a public record under Chapter 132 of the General
48 Statutes or under G.S. 58-2-100 and is confidential and privileged.
49 "§ 58-56A-23. Pharmacy desert reporting requirements.
50 (a) The Department of Insurance shall identify any pharmacy deserts.
