6 PART VIII. CONSUMERS TO RECEIVE THE BENEFIT OF PHARMACY REBATES
7 FOR PRESCRIPTION DRUGS
8 SECTION 8.1. Article 3 of Chapter 58 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
9 a new section to read:
10 "§ 58-3-182. Consumer protections/prescription cost-sharing.
11 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
12 (1) Defined cost-sharing. – A deductible payment or coinsurance amount imposed
13 on an insured for a prescription drug that is covered under the insured's health
14 benefit plan.
15 (2) Reserved for future codification purposes.
16 (3) Reserved for future codification purposes.
17 (4) Rebate. – A formulary discount or price concession attributable to the
18 utilization of prescription drugs in the State and that is paid by a manufacturer
19 to a pharmacy benefits manager.
20 (b) When calculating an insured's defined cost-sharing for a covered prescription drug at
21 the point of sale, an insurer offering a health benefit plan shall base the calculation on the price
22 of the prescription drug after taking into account all rebates associated with that prescription
23 drug. The price of the prescription drug shall be reduced by an amount equal to ninety percent
24 (90%) of all rebates received, or to be received, in conjunction with the dispensing or
25 administration of the prescription drug.
26 (c) Nothing in this section shall preclude an insurer from decreasing an insured's defined
27 cost-sharing by an amount greater than that required under this section.
28 (d) By January 1 of each year, each insurer offering a health benefit plan shall submit to
29 the Commissioner a certification attesting that, for all health benefit plans offered in this State by
30 the insurer, the insurer has complied with the requirements of this section. The Commissioner
31 shall establish the form to be utilized for this certification.
32 (e) Failure to complete the certification or comply with any of the other requirements
33 under this section is a violation subject to G.S. 58-2-70. Each day that an insurer fails to complete
34 the certification is considered a separate violation.
35 (f) A violation of this section is an unfair trade practice under Article 63 of this Chapter
36 and under G.S. 75-1.1 and is subject to all of the enforcement and penalty provisions of an unfair
37 trade practice under this Chapter and under Article 1 of Chapter 75 of the General Statutes."
38 SECTION 8.2. G.S. 58-56A-3 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
39 "(c3) G.S. 58-3-182 applies to pharmacy benefits managers when calculating an insured's
40 out-of-pocket cost for a covered prescription drug."
41 SECTION 8.3 This Part is effective January 1, 2027, and applies to prescription
42 drugs purchased by insureds on or after that date.
43
44 PART IX. PRESCRIPTION DRUG TRANSPARENCY
45 SECTION 9.(a) Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
46 Article to read:
47 "Article 4D.
48 "Prescription Drug Transparency.
49 "§ 90-85.55. Definitions.
50 The following definitions apply in this Article:
51 (1) Interested parties. – All of the following:
Senate Bill 479-Fifth Edition Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. State agencies that (i) purchase prescription drugs or (ii) employ
2 prescribers.
3 b. Health insurance companies.
4 c. Health care service plan providers.
5 d. Pharmacy benefits managers.
6 (2) Manufacturer. – An entity or an agent of an entity that produces, prepares,
7 propagates, compounds, processes, packages, repackages, or labels a
8 brand-name or generic drug. "Manufacturer" does not include an entity
9 engaged in the preparation and dispensing of a brand-name or generic drug
10 pursuant to a prescription.
11 (3) Prescriber. – Any person authorized under the laws of this State to issue a
12 prescription order.
13 (4) Prescription drug. – Defined in G.S. 90-85.3.
14 (5) Prescription order. – Defined in G.S. 90-85.3.
15 (6) Price. – The wholesale acquisition cost as defined in 42 U.S.C. §
16 1395w-3a(c)(6)(B).
17 (7) Secretary. – The Secretary of the Department of Health and Human Services.
18 "§ 90-85.56. Required notifications and disclosures.
19 (a) Price Increases. – By January 31 of each year, a manufacturer shall notify all
20 interested parties of each increase in price of fifteen percent (15%) or greater that occurred in the
21 prior calendar year for a prescription drug with a price of one hundred dollars ($100.00) or more
22 for a 30-day supply. The manufacturer shall disclose all of the following to interested parties for
23 each drug price increase noticed for the prior calendar year under this subsection:
24 (1) The date and price of acquisition of the drug, if it was not developed by the
25 manufacturer.
26 (2) A schedule of price increases for the drug for the five years prior to the
27 calendar year for which the drug price increase was required to be noticed
28 under this subsection.
29 (b) New Products. – A manufacturer shall notify all interested parties of the price of any
30 new prescription drug within three days after it is made available for purchase in this State.
31 Within 30 days after the notification required by this subsection, the manufacturer shall disclose
32 to interested parties the date and price of acquisition of the drug if it was not developed by the
33 manufacturer.
34 (c) Satisfaction of Obligations. – A manufacturer's obligations under this section shall be
35 fully satisfied by the submission of information and data that a manufacturer includes in its
36 annual consolidated report on Securities and Exchange Commission Form 10-K or any other
37 public disclosure.
38 (d) Information is Not Public Record. – Information provided to the Secretary or an
39 interested party pursuant to this section shall, except to the extent it is already in the public
40 domain, be considered trade secret under Article 24 of Chapter 66 of the General Statutes,
41 confidential, exempt from public inspection and copying under Chapter 132 of the General
42 Statutes, and shall not be disclosed directly or indirectly. The Secretary, interested parties, and
43 their agents shall not publish or otherwise disclose any information that would allow for the
44 identification of an individual drug, therapeutic class of drugs, or manufacturer, that would reveal
45 the prices of any drug or therapeutic class of drugs, or that has the potential to compromise the
46 financial, competitive, or proprietary nature of any information submitted by the manufacturer
47 pursuant to this section. The Secretary and interested parties shall impose the confidentiality
48 protections of this section on any downstream third party that may receive or otherwise have
49 access to this information.
50 "§ 90-85.57. Penalty for failure to report.
Page 18 Senate Bill 479-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 The Secretary shall assess a civil penalty against any manufacturer failing to report the
2 information required by this Article. The amount of the penalty shall not exceed one thousand
3 dollars ($1,000) for each day the manufacturer fails to submit the required information. The clear
4 proceeds of any civil penalties assessed pursuant to this section shall be remitted to the Civil
5 Penalty and Forfeiture Fund in accordance with G.S. 115C-457.2. Chapter 150B of the General
6 Statutes applies to proceedings for the assessment of civil penalties under this section.
7 "§ 90-85.58. Report and data collection by the Secretary; public portal.
8 (a) Plan for Implementation. – The Secretary shall develop a plan to collect data from
9 manufacturers pursuant to G.S. 90-85.56 to provide transparency and accountability for
10 prescription drug pricing. The Secretary shall consult with other state and national agencies and
11 nonprofit organizations to determine how to implement this data collection directive but shall not
12 disclose any confidential, proprietary, or trade secret information.
13 (b) Public Portal. – The Secretary shall create an online portal to provide the public with
14 access to the notifications, reports, and other disclosures required by this Article.
15 (c) Annual Report. – Beginning January 1, 2027, and annually thereafter, the Secretary
16 shall report to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services the
17 following information with respect to prescription drugs sold in this State:
18 (1) The 25 drugs prescribed most frequently in the State.
19 (2) The 25 most costly drugs based on the total amount spent on those drugs by
20 consumers in this State.
21 (3) The 25 drugs with the greatest percentage cost increases during the prior
22 calendar year.
23 (4) The 10 manufacturers with the greatest average percentage cost increase for
24 the prior calendar year for all drugs sold by that manufacturer in the State."
25 SECTION 9.(b) This Part is effective when it becomes law.
26
27 PART X. PHARMACY REPORTING REQUIREMENTS
28 SECTION 10. Article 4A of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by
29 adding a new section to read:
30 "§ 90-85.42. Board of Pharmacy reporting.
31 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
32 (1) Large retail pharmacy. – More than 25 pharmacies in common ownership.
33 (2) Small retail pharmacy. – Twenty-five or fewer pharmacies in common
34 ownership.
35 (b) Reporting Requirements. – No later than October 1 of each year, the Board shall
36 report the following information to the Department of Insurance and the Joint Legislative
37 Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services:
38 (1) The current number of licensed pharmacies in the State.
39 (2) The number of small retail pharmacies that have opened in the preceding five
40 years.
41 (3) The number of large retail pharmacies that have opened in the preceding five
42 years.
43 (4) The number of small retail pharmacies that have closed in the preceding five
44 years.
45 (5) The number of large retail pharmacies that have closed in the preceding five
46 years."
47
48 PART XI. RFP CHANGES
49 SECTION 11.(a) Article 3B of Chapter 135 of the General Statutes is amended by
50 adding a new section to read:
51 "§ 135-49. Pharmacy benefits manager contracts.
Senate Bill 479-Fifth Edition Page 19

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 The Executive Administrator shall consider incorporating the following items into a request
2 for proposal for a pharmacy benefits manager for the Plan:
3 (1) Allowing the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to provide a monetary
4 advantage to pharmacies in North Carolina neighborhoods, communities, and
5 counties that are underserved by pharmacies.
6 (2) Requiring the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to annually report all of the
7 information required in G.S. 58-56A-22 to the State Treasurer, Commissioner
8 of Insurance, and Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and
9 Human Services no later than May 1 of each year.
10 (3) Preventing the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers from contractually
11 requiring independent pharmacies to accept reimbursement for a drug, device,
12 or pharmacy service in an amount that is less than the acquisition cost of the
13 drug, device, or pharmacy service.
14 (4) Requiring the Plan and the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to adhere to the
15 coverage requirements of G.S. 58-56A-55.
16 (5) Requiring the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to act as a fiduciary in
17 accordance with G.S. 58-56A-21.
18 (6) Requiring the Plan and the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to adhere to the
19 pharmacy of choice provisions of G.S. 58-51-37.
20 (7) Requiring the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to meet or exceed the
21 Medicare Part D program standards for convenient access to network
22 pharmacies under 42 C.F.R. § 423.120.
23 (8) Requiring the Plan's pharmacy benefits managers to reimburse affiliated and
24 non-affiliated pharmacies on the same terms.
25 (9) Adhering to the cost-sharing consumer protection provisions of
26 G.S. 58-3-182."
27 SECTION 11.(b) This Part becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to
28 requests for proposals issued on or after that date.
29
30 PART XII. EFFECTIVE DATE
31 SECTION 12.1. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
32 law.
